answers.body_markdown:
A direct translation would be:

    for i in range(3, int(math.sqrt(n)), 2):
        if n % i == 0:
            return False

Use a basic Python `for i in range` loop:

    for i in range(3, math.round(math.sqrt(x)), 2):
        if (n % i == 0):
            return false

In a Java for loop, the step (the `i += 2` part in your example) occurs at the end of the loop, just before it repeats. Translated to a while, your for loop would be equivalent to:

    int i = 3;
    while (i &lt; Math.sqrt(n)) {
        if (n % i == 0) {
            return false;
        }
        i += 2;
    }

Which in Python is similar:

    i = 3
    while i &lt; math.sqrt(n):
        if n % i == 0:
            return False
        i += 2

However, you can make this more &quot;Pythonic&quot; and easier to read by using Python&#39;s [`xrange`](http://docs.python.org/2/library/functions.html#xrange) function, which allows you to specify a `step` parameter:

    for i in xrange(3, math.sqrt(n), 2):
        if n % i == 0:
            return False

I get this answer from an automatic translation by AgileUML: 

    def op(self, n) :
      result = False
      i = 0
      i = 3
      while i &lt; math.sqrt(n) :
        if n % i == 0 :
          return False
        else :
          pass
        i = (i + 2)
      return True

It seems to be semantically correct?

